    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "The trajectory is asymmetric and the period is noticeably longer than the small-angle value — both classic large-amplitude pendulum effects. The amplitude decays because of the $-b\\omega$ damping term in the model.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 4. Arbitrary input via lambda\n\n`mod_simulate_nonlinear` takes any input function `lambda([t], [u1, u2, ...])`. Here's a sinusoidal torque (with the pendulum starting from rest):",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "[t_sin, y_sin] : mod_simulate_nonlinear(m, [0.0, 0.0],\n                                         lambda([t], [3*sin(2*t)]),\n                                         8.0)$\n\nax_draw2d(\n  color=\"red\", line_width=2, name=\"theta(t)\",\n  lines(t_sin, y_sin),\n  color=\"gray\", dash=\"dash\", name=\"3 sin(2t) (input)\",\n  explicit(3*sin(2*t), t, 0, 8),\n  title=\"Pendulum forced by tau(t) = 3 sin(2t)\",\n  xlabel=\"t (s)\", ylabel=\"theta (rad)  /  tau (N·m)\",\n  grid=true, showlegend=true\n)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 5,
